(1209, 413, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you clearly understand the cost structure of your business. This implies that you have clarity regarding which costs are fixed in nature and which are&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">variable. It&#39;s crucial that you understand the cost structure for your business so you can find ways to reduce your costs, increase your profits and keep your business&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">running.</span></span></p>\r\n', '5', 'Cost Structure'),
(1210, 413, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you do not clearly understand the cost structure of your business. This implies that you do not have clarity regarding which costs are fixed in nature&nbsp; and which are variable. &nbsp;It&#39;s crucial that you understand the cost structure for your business so you can find ways to reduce your costs, increase your profits and keep your business running. You should sit with your consultant and bifurcate the costs into fixed and variable as it will help you in pricing your products well.</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', 'Cost Structure'),
(1211, 414, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you are aware of the break even point. &nbsp;The break-even point is the point where you have sold sufficient products or services to cover your costs&nbsp;during an accounting period. &nbsp;It&#39;s possible that a business could be churning over a lot of money, but still be making a loss. By understanding your break-even point and the&nbsp;level of sales needed to create profits, you can make better decisions around pricing (e.g. whether price reductions can be made or if price increases can be absorbed).&nbsp;Knowing your break-even point allows you to price your products and services or experiences to meet your business needs.The higher your business is above its break-even&nbsp;point can help show how strong the business is.&nbsp;It helps in the following:&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Pricing</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Simplify raising funds</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Setting revenue targets&nbsp;</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Reduce risk</span></span><br />\r\n	<strong><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Action to be taken</span></span></strong>\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Work out your break-even point for each activity or product to see if you have made a profit or loss. This will help you identify any poorly performing products or services that are being carried by more profitable ones. You can then consider eliminating marginal activities and fine-tune your more profitable activities</span></span></li>\r\n		<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Meet with your accountant or consultant to check and review your break-even calculations.</span></span></li>\r\n		<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Reduce your break-even point by lowering your overheads. Lowering your fixed costs will help you increase your profit margin. Go through all of your fixed costs one-by-one and see where you can make reductions.</span></span></li>\r\n		<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Can you increase your prices? Investigate if your pricing is right and then see where you can make any small adjustments.&nbsp;</span></span></li>\r\n		<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Calculate what you could afford to lose in business by raising your prices, and then decide if it is a viable option for you.</span></span></li>\r\n		<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Determine if you can source cheaper supplies or materials without impacting the product or service quality. Asking all your suppliers to re-quote could see a&nbsp; cost-saving which will also lower your break-even point.</span></span></li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', '5', 'Break-Even Point'),
(1212, 414, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you are not aware of the break even point. &nbsp;The break-even point is the point where you have sold sufficient products or services to cover your costs&nbsp; during an accounting period. It&#39;s possible that a business could be turning over a lot of money, but still be making a loss. By understanding your break-even point and the level of sales needed to create profits, you can make better decisions around pricing (e.g. whether price reductions can be made or if price increases can be absorbed).&nbsp; Knowing your break-even point allows you to price your products and services or experiences to meet your business needs. The higher your business is above its break&nbsp; even point can help show how strong the business is.&nbsp;It helps in the following:&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Pricing</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Simplify raising funds</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Setting revenue targets&nbsp;</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Reduce risk</span></span><br />\r\n	<strong><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Action to be taken</span></span></strong>\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Work out your break-even point for each activity or product to see if you&#39;ve made a profit or loss. This will help you identify any poorly performing products or services that are being carried by more profitable ones. You can then consider eliminating marginal activities and fine-tune your more profitable activities</span></span></li>\r\n		<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Meet with your accountant or consultant to check and review your break-even calculations</span></span></li>\r\n		<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Reduce your break-even point by lowering your overheads. Lowering your fixed costs will help you increase your profit margin. Go through all of your fixed costs one-by-one and see where you can make reductions.</span></span></li>\r\n		<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Can you increase your prices? Investigate if your pricing is right and then see where you can make any small adjustments.&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Calculate what you could afford to lose in business by raising your prices, and then decide if it is a viable option for you.</span></span></li>\r\n		<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Determine if you can source cheaper supplies or materials without impacting the product or service quality. Asking all your suppliers to re-quote could see a cost-saving which will also lower your break-even point.</span></span></li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', '0', 'Break-even point'),
(1213, 415, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You are doing good in terms of measuring sales growth percentage monthly. This helps in knowing in which direction the company is going and also help in assessing the actions required to achieve monthly sales growth.</span></span></p>\r\n', '3', 'Sales Growth'),
(1214, 415, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Sales growth percentage should be monitored monthly . This will help in knowing in which direction the company is going and will also help in assessing the actions required to achieve monthly sales growth.</span></span></p>\r\n', '1', 'Sales Growth'),
(1215, 416, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You are doing good in terms of measuring GP percentage on a monthly basis. This helps in knowing the trend. If GP trend is showing a decreasing trend then it is a&nbsp;matter of concern which should be immediately addressed. On the contrary, if it is showing an increasing trend then an analysis should be done to find out the reason for&nbsp;higher GP. This will help in further growth of the company.</span></span></p>\r\n', '3', 'Gross Profit'),
(1216, 416, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">GP percentage should be tracked on a monthly basis. This helps in knowing the trend. If GP trend is showing a decreasing trend then it is a matter of concern which&nbsp;should be immediately addressed. On the contrary if it is showing an increasing trend then an analysis should be done to find out the reason for higher GP. This will help in&nbsp;further growth of the company.</span></span></p>\r\n', '1', 'Gross Profit'),
(1217, 417, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You are doing good in terms of measuring NP percentage on a monthly basis. This helps in knowing the trend. If the NP percentage is decreasing then it is a matter of&nbsp; concern. A thorough analysis should be done to find out the causes and corrective action should be taken promptly. On the other hand, if the NP percentage is increasing then an analysis should be done to find out the reason and steps should be taken if possible, to further enhance it.</span></span></p>\r\n', '3', 'Net Profit'),
(1218, 417, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Net Profit percentage should be tracked on a monthly basis. This will help in knowing the trend. If the NP percentage is decreasing then it is a matter of concern. A&nbsp;thorough analysis should be done to find out the causes and corrective action should be taken promptly. On the other hand, if the NP percentage is increasing then an&nbsp;analysis should be done to find out the reason and steps should be taken if possible, to further enhance it.</span></span></p>\r\n', '1', 'Net Profit'),
(1219, 418, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You are doing good in terms of measuring ROI percentage on a monthly basis. This helps in knowing the exact return that you are getting on your money. This will help&nbsp;you evaluate whether the business is generating enough returns or the money needs to be invested elsewhere to generate returns.</span></span></p>\r\n', '3', 'Return on Investment'),
(1220, 418, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">ROI should be monitored on a monthly basis so as to know the exact return that you are getting on your money. This will help you evaluate whether the business is&nbsp;generating enough returns or the money needs to be invested elsewhere to generate returns.</span></span></p>\r\n', '1', 'Return on Investment'),
(1221, 419, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Using financial ratios to measure your business performance is a must for any company. Doing comparative analysis on an ongoing basis is the very best way to spot&nbsp;anomalies that may not otherwise be apparent to you. Solely using hard numbers as your key measure is extremely limiting. It simply does not offer the level of insight you need into how your business is performing.</span></span></p>\r\n', '3', 'Financial Ratios'),
(1222, 419, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Using financial ratios to measure your business performance is a must for any company. Doing comparative analysis on an ongoing basis is the very best way to spot&nbsp;anomalies that may not otherwise be apparent to you. Solely using hard numbers as your key measure is extremely limiting. It simply does not offer the level of insight you&nbsp;need into how your business is performing.</span></span></p>\r\n', '1', 'Financial Ratios'),
(1223, 420, 'Upwards\r\n', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Since inventory days are increasing, it means that you are investing significantly in building up your inventory levels. There is a significant cost to doing this and you&nbsp;need to ensure that profit levels are adequate to cover this or that short-term lines of credit can be put in place to fund inventory growth.</span></span></p>\r\n', '1', 'Inventory'),
(1224, 420, 'Downwards \r\n', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Since inventory days are decreasing, it may be a reflection of a just-in-time strategy or simply buoyant sales.</span></span></p>\r\n', '5', 'Inventory'),
(1225, 420, 'No Change \r\n', 'yellowbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Since inventory level remains static it means that you maintain the same level of inventory on average from one period to the next. This assists in accurate cash flow&nbsp; forecasting. Further this does not mean that you should not think of getting it down further as it will help improve your working capital cycle.</span></span></p>\r\n', '3', 'Inventory'),
(1226, 421, 'Yes', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Since you are having obsolete inventory, steps should be taken on an immediate basis to dispose off the obsolete inventory. Obsolete inventory increases cost of storage and blocking of working capital. It is better to dispose these at the earliest and ploy the working capital in faster moving inventory.</span></span></p>\r\n', '1', ''),
(1227, 421, 'No', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">It is a good sign that you are not having any obsolete inventory. It implies that you have managed your inventory well.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '5', ''),
(1228, 421, 'Not Applicable', '', '<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Nil</span></span></p>\r\n', '5', ''),
(1229, 422, 'yes', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you have excessive exposure in debtors to any customer or small group of customers. This implies that company is subject to high risk in case this customer or this group of customers either reduce or completely stop working with the company. Steps should be taken to diversify and add more customers. This will help to mitigate risk.</span></span></p>\r\n', '1', 'Debtors'),
(1230, 422, 'no', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you do not have excessive exposure in debtors to any customer or small group of customers. It is good that the company is not dependant on few customers or a group of customers. This lends more stability to the company.</span></span></p>\r\n', '5', 'Debtors'),
(1231, 423, 'Stable\r\n', 'yellowbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You have mentioned that your accounts receivable days are stable. You should analyse in terms of other factors affecting the receivable days, whether the stability is good for company or you need to work towards decreasing the same.</span></span></p>\r\n', '3', ''),
(1232, 423, 'Decreasing\r\n', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Receivable days are decreasing. This may simply be a seasonal issue or effective credit control on the part of your business. It may also reflect the mix of cash sales increasing relative to credit sales. Generally, it is not something to worry about.</span></span></p>\r\n', '5', ''),
(1233, 423, 'Increasing\r\n', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Receivable days are increasing. This is an early warning sign that needs to be heeded. If there is a significant increase in receivable days, it indicates poor credit control on the part of your business or increasing levels of risk being assumed by your business. Watch out for emerging bad debts.</span></span></p>\r\n', '1', ''),
(1234, 424, 'yes', '', '<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Nil</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', ''),
(1235, 424, 'no', '', '<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Nil</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', ''),
(1236, 425, 'Decreasing\r\n', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\">Decreasing of bad debts is a good sign for the company. However, you should further analyse it in light of industry average. &nbsp;You should not become complacent by this and should continuously implement systems and strategies which will further help in reducing it</span></span>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '4', ''),
(1237, 425, 'Constant\r\n', 'yellowbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Bad debts at constant rate will in itself not give you a clear picture. &nbsp;You should further analyse it in light of industry average. You should not become complacent by this and should continuously implement systems and strategies which will further help in reducing it.</span></span></p>\r\n', '2', ''),
(1238, 425, 'Increasing\r\n', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Increase in bad debt is alarming. You need to immediately find out the reason for the same and implement systems and strategies which will help in reducing it to an optimum level. In case you are struggling with high bad debts or facing collection problems get in touch with us to improve your collection system.</span></span></p>\r\n', '1', ''),
(1239, 425, 'Not applicable', '', '<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Nil</span></span></p>\r\n', '4', ''),
(1240, 426, 'yes', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that there is large concentration in a small number of vendors. Steps should be taken to find out more vendors. This will help you in better pricing as well as help in smooth functioning in case there are some issues at vendor end.</span></span></p>\r\n', '2', 'Creditors'),
(1241, 426, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that there is no large concentration in a small number of vendors. It is good that business is not dependant on few large vendors. This lends more stability as well as aids in better pricing for the business.</span></span></p>\r\n', '4', 'Creditors'),
(1242, 427, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Since there are no payables outstanding for longer than credit terms, is positive and indicates that the cash flow within the business is fundamentally sound.</span></span></p>\r\n', '4', '');
INSERT INTO `options` (`id`, `question_id`, `options`, `option_bullet`, `option_answer`, `option_point`, `option_header`) VALUES
(1243, 427, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you have payables outstanding longer than agreed terms. Pushing out of payables beyond normal terms usually signifies cash flow difficulties within the business. This can be destructive to established business relationships with suppliers and should be avoided if possible. If you are overtrading &ndash; growing sales quicker than you can finance inventory and payables then you should cut back on sales growth or other forms of financing should be considered.</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', ''),
(1244, 428, 'Increasing\r\n', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You indicated that Accounts Payable Days are Increasing slightly. A modest increase here may simply be a function of your accounts payable function being busy. It could also be a reflection of some timing differences in relation to receivables.</span></span></p>\r\n', '1', ''),
(1245, 428, 'Decreasing\r\n', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You indicated that your Accounts Payable Days are decreasing. This is a somewhat unusual scenario because it means you are paying your creditors much faster than they require. Unless you are getting significant discounts for paying early you should perhaps consider investing your short-term cash surpluses in short term investment&nbsp; instruments until such time as you need to pay your creditors.</span></span></p>\r\n', '5', ''),
(1246, 428, 'Stable\r\n', 'yellowbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You indicated that Accounts Payable days are stable. When accounts payable days are consistent over time it usually means that you are within terms and that there is no pressure on your business to accelerate payments.</span></span></p>\r\n', '3', ''),
(1247, 429, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Since tax liabilities are paid on time is a good sign</span></span></p>\r\n', '4', 'Taxation Liabilities'),
(1248, 429, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Pending tax liabilities is not a good sign. It implies that either there is cash shortage or may be compliances are not happening in time.</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', 'Taxation Liabilities'),
(1249, 430, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Since contingent liabilities are reflected in the accounts, it is a good sign.</span></span></p>\r\n', '4', 'Contingent Liabilities'),
(1250, 430, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Contingent liabilities are not provided in your accounts. Not only should you provide for contingent liabilities in your accounts, you should also make a quantitative assessment of the probability of it coming to reality and make a specific provision based on the probability. If it goes away, then the provision can be written back to your profit and loss account. This will help in creating a more realistic financial picture of the business.</span></span></p>\r\n', '1', 'Contingent Liabilities'),
(1251, 431, 'yes', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Since there are legal claims outstanding that could have a significant impact in increasing your current liabilities, provision should be created for all legal claims outstanding so that the company is able to run smoothly even if these claims become payable.</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', ''),
(1252, 431, 'no', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Since there are no legal claims outstanding right now is a good sign. Even if some claim arises in future, company should create adequate provision so that business can run smoothly in the eventuality of these claims become a reality.</span></span></p>\r\n', '4', ''),
(1253, 432, 'Upwards \r\n', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Since profit is trending upwards, is a very good sign. You can analyse the reasons and continue on the same path.</span></span></p>\r\n', '5', 'Profitability trends'),
(1254, 432, 'Downwards\r\n', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Since profit is trending downwards, is not a good sign. You can analyse the reasons for the downfall and take necessary corrective action.</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', 'Profitability trends'),
(1255, 432, 'Static\r\n', 'yellowbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Since profit is static, is not a good sign. The primary aim of any business should be growth in Profit. You can analyse the reasons for profit being static and take&nbsp;necessary corrective action.</span></span></p>\r\n', '3', 'Profitability trends'),
(1256, 433, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you understand cost per employee. You obviously recognize the importance of knowing the total cost of each employee. This includes salary, benefits and allocated overheads. The next step is to use objective measures to identify how much each individual employee is generating for the business. This is&nbsp;not just about sales staff. There is an economic value and it&rsquo;s a measure of the contribution made by every employee regardless of their role. Unless you are getting a positive return on investment on each employee in value terms, &nbsp;you may need to re-evaluate if you have the right employees doing the right jobs.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '4', 'Cost Per Employee'),
(1257, 433, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you do not understand cost per employee. Perhaps this is something you should be taking a close look at. Once you know the total costof each employee, which includes salary, benefits and allocated overhead, the next step is to use objective measures to identify how much each individual employee is&nbsp;generating for the business. This is not just about sales staff. There is an economic value and it&rsquo;s a measure of the contribution made by every employee regardless of their&nbsp;role. Unless you are getting a positive return on investment on each employee in value terms, you may need to re-evaluate if you have the right employees doing the right&nbsp;jobs.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '2', 'Cost Per Employee'),
(1258, 434, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you have an effective accounts payables (AP) and accounts receivables (AR) policies. To have effective well laid out AR and AP policies is a must for every business. The same should be written and approved by the appropriate authority.</span></span></p>\r\n', '5', 'Accounts Receivable and Payables Policies'),
(1259, 434, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you have an effective accounts payables (AP) and accounts receivables (AR) policies. It is imperative for all business to have a very clearly laid out policies regarding AR and AP. The same should be written and approved by the appropriate authority.</span></span></p>\r\n', '2', 'Accounts Receivable and Payables Policies'),
(1260, 435, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">This meets with best business practice. It is imperative that you seek to shorten the cash conversion cycle to its lowest possible value so that each rupee you invest in&nbsp;sales comes back to you in cash revenue as quickly as possible.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '5', 'Cash Conversion Cycle'),
(1261, 435, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You need to take a careful look at how much cash you have tied up in inventory and receivables on an ongoing basis. If you sell to customers on credit, you have to finance the inventory and receivables until the customer eventually pays you and the cash arrives in your business bank account. There may be the additional cost of an&nbsp;overdraft or line of credit for the duration from credit sale to cash in bank. The shorter the cycle can be maintained, the better it will be for your business.</span></span></p>\r\n', '1', 'Cash Conversion Cycle'),
(1262, 436, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you have considered changing your business model. You should ask yourself the following questions:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Why you wanted to change your existing business model</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">What result you were not getting from your existing model</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Once you have answers to this, you can change your business model by:</span></span>\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">adding new services or products</span></span></li>\r\n		<li><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">collaborating with other partners</span></span></li>\r\n		<li><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">exploring new suppliers</span></span></li>\r\n		<li><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">opening to new market</span></span></li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', '5', 'Business Model'),
(1263, 436, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you have not considered changing your business model. You should ask yourself the following questions:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Are you getting the desired results from your existing model?</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Are there any elements which can be tweaked in the business model which can give a better result?</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Once you have answers to this, you can if required change your business model by:</span></span>\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>&nbsp;<span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">adding new services or products</span></span></li>\r\n		<li><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">collaborating with other partners</span></span></li>\r\n		<li><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">exploring new suppliers</span></span></li>\r\n		<li><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">opening to new markets.</span></span></li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', '1', 'Business Model'),
(1264, 437, 'Significant Cash Surplus', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you have significant cash surplus in your business. In these challenging times it is a major achievement to have significant cash surpluses in a&nbsp;business and this augurs well for the future of your business.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '20', 'Funds Availability '),
(1265, 437, 'Moderate Cash Surplus  ', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you have moderate cash surplus in your business. In these challenging times it is good to have moderate cash surpluses in a business and this augurs well for the future of your business.</span></span></p>\r\n', '15', 'Funds Availability '),
(1266, 437, 'No Cash Surpluses', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Having no cash surpluses can be an uncomfortable position to be in unless you have access to bank funding or investor funds. Funding growth in your business is&nbsp;dependent on external financing.&nbsp; We cannot over-emphasize the importance of business planning and effective financial management of your business. Nobody likes&nbsp;surprises and at least if you plan for contingencies, however, unlikely they may seem to be, you will be half way to addressing the problems when they occur without warning.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', 'Funds Availability '),
(1267, 437, 'Investor Funds Available', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you have access to investor funds. Make sure that this is not just wishful thinking and seek written commitment from any potential investors or&nbsp;investment brokers.&nbsp;We cannot over-emphasize the importance of business planning and effective financial management of your business. Nobody likes surprises and at least if you plan for contingencies, however, unlikely they may seem to be, you will be half way to addressing the problems when they occur without warning.</span></span></p>\r\n', '5', 'Funds Availability '),
(1268, 437, 'Adequate Bank Funding Available', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that adequate bank funding is available to you. If you retain the support of your bankers your liquidity and access to capital should sustain your business&nbsp;through difficult times. You should also consider having lines of credit with more than one financial institution to provide you with a level of flexibility and comfort. We&nbsp;cannot over-emphasize the importance of business planning and effective financial&nbsp;management of your business. Nobody likes surprises and at least if you plan for contingencies, however, unlikely they may seem to be, you will be half way to addressing&nbsp;the problems when they occur without warning.</span></span></p>\r\n', '5', 'Funds Availability '),
(1269, 437, 'Inadequate Bank Funding Available ', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that adequate bank funding is not available. This is something that you need to rectify. It is always a good idea to have an overdraft or line of credit&nbsp;established with your bank to cater for unplanned shocks in your business or the market. To facilitate this, you should be able to demonstrate strong financial management&nbsp;skills. At a minimum, you will need a strong business plan supported by financial budgets and cash flow projections. We cannot over-emphasize the importance of business&nbsp;planning and effective financial management of your business. Nobody likes surprises and at least if you plan for contingencies, however, unlikely they may seem to be,&nbsp;you will be half way to addressing the problems when they occur without warning.</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', 'Funds Availability '),
(1270, 437, 'No Funding Available', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that no funding is available to you. If you do not have support from your bank and if there is a decline in the speed with which you can turn your&nbsp;receivables into cash, then your business could find itself in a lot of trouble once your moderate cash surplus runs out. To facilitate an application for bank or equity&nbsp;funding, you should be able to demonstrate strong financial management skills. At a minimum, you will need a strong business plan supported by financial budgets and&nbsp;cash flow projections. We cannot over-emphasize the importance of business planning and effective financial management of your business. Nobody likes surprises and at&nbsp;least if you plan for contingencies, however, unlikely they may seem to be, you will be half way to addressing the problems when they occur without warning.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', 'Funds Availability '),
(1271, 438, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you have access to bank finance. It is a good sign for any company that it has access to bank finance. This means the company has good credit rating,&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">sufficient security to give to Bankers. Since the company can avail bank finance, it is not necessary that it takes funding from Bank. Such a decision would be dependant on&nbsp;multiple factors. In case you want to know more about when and how to take bank funding , you can get in touch with any of our experts.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '10', 'Bank Funding '),
(1272, 438, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Since the company is not in a position to raise funds from banks it suggests that either the credit rating is not good or the company does have adequate assets to offer as security. It is very critical to find out the reasons and take appropriate action to overcome those.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', 'Bank Funding '),
(1273, 439, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Since the bank funding facility is fully utilised, the company should work on reducing such debt as also try and identify other sources through which it can raise funds if required.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', ''),
(1274, 439, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Since the bank funding is not fully utilised, the company has an option to raise further funds from Banks if required. You should do a detailed cost benefit analysis of various sources of funds and arrive at an optimum capital structure.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '5', ''),
(1275, 440, 'yes', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you do overtrading at times. Overtrading happens when a business is selling more goods that it can afford to fund from cash and receivables. It simply means that you are growing the business too fast. A lot of businesses do this from time to time but can only sustain it for short periods before cash shortfalls become an issue. You need to continue to be able to pay your suppliers when their invoices fall due for payment. If you tie up too much cash in inventory and receivables you will not be able to do this. The simple answer here is to consolidate your sales at a level that does not put undue pressure on the business&rsquo;s financial resources.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', 'Overtrading '),
(1276, 440, 'no', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you do not indulge in over trading. Overtrading happens when a business is selling more goods that it can afford to fund from cash and receivables. You are maintaining sales at a level which the business can afford to finance. We would suggest you check that the finances are optimally utilised.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '5', 'Overtrading '),
(1277, 441, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">The financing is well spread amongst financiers. This is best business practice. Always ensure that you have several lines of credit from different financial institutions, even if you do not need the credit right away</span></span></p>\r\n', '10', 'Finance Providers '),
(1278, 441, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Financing is not well spread amongst providers. This can become an absolutely critical choice for any business. If you place all of your lines of credit with a single financial institution this means that you only have a track record with a single financial institution. If your sole provider of bank credit decides that you have reached the&nbsp;limit of your borrowing with that institution, you may have nowhere else to turn, particularly if you have a pressing need for cash. This can be the death of any business.&nbsp;Instead, make sure that you spread your banking business across a number of providers and put several lines of credit in place, even if you do not need them right now. &nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', 'Finance Providers '),
(1279, 442, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that the owners are in a position to infuse funds if required from their personal resources. It is always comforting for the company to know that the owners have deep pockets and that they can look upto them in case some funds are required.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '10', 'Owner’s Funds '),
(1280, 442, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Since the owners are not in a position to pump in the money, it is imperative for the company to judiciously use the funds available as they cannot look upto the owners to induce money in the company.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', 'Owner’s Funds '),
(1281, 443, 'yes', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">It is important to ensure you have enough working capital to keep your business operational until you are able to run at a profit. Once your business is profitable, you will need to manage your borrowings and loans carefully. It will usually be in your best interest to limit your drawings from the business and focus on reducing loans and debts.&nbsp;Start with those that carry the highest interest rate.&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">The size and age of your creditors&rsquo; book has important implications for your business cash flow and should be something you monitor regularly to avoid any nasty surprises.&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You can take the following actions:&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">See if you can re-finance any short-term debt into longer-term debt, which should reduce the amount of interest you are&nbsp;paying.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Take a long, hard look at all your products and services to see what is&nbsp;making the most profit, and then focus on driving these sales above all others.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Use surplus cash sparingly &ndash; see if you can lease, rent or borrow what you need in the short-term to preserve your cash.&nbsp;</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Measure profit, not sales. Rather than chasing sales, concentrate on selling what generates the largest margin for your business.&nbsp;</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Look at cutting your costs. If you are continually borrowing more money than your business can generate, then you have the balance wrong. If sales are falling, you MUST cut overheads so your business can survive. Review costs such as staff, offices, and company cars, plus any advertising you do not&nbsp;measure.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Review your own salary. Be careful of draining too much money out of your business in the form of personal drawings, particularly during the leaner cash flow months.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Communicate clearly to staff any changes in the way the business is going to be run.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Review your expenses policy. Sales people usually have the highest expenses so make sure they understand what the rules are.&nbsp;</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Check staff expense claims in detail and be prepared to address staff who are ignoring your expenses policy.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Consider invoice financing. This ensures you get paid immediately and the burden of the chasing passes to a third party, such as your bank.</span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', '0', 'Excess Borrowings '),
(1282, 443, 'no', 'greenbullet.png', '<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">It is prudent on your part to not get into a situation of excess borrowings.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '10', 'Excess Borrowings '),
(1283, 444, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you are regularly getting credit rating done. Getting company rated by a reputed credit rating agency helps company to identify gaps so that&nbsp;corrective action can be taken. It also helps in raising funds.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '5', 'Credit Rating '),
(1284, 444, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you are not regularly getting credit rating done. Getting company rated by a reputed credit rating agency helps company to identify gaps so that&nbsp;corrective action can be taken. It also helps in raising funds.</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', 'Credit Rating '),
(1285, 445, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you have enough cash reserves or forward orders to survive in the short term. To survive unforeseen emergencies, every business needs a cash reserve or secure and profitable forward orders that will cover the operating costs of the business.</span></span></p>\r\n', '15', 'Cash Reserves and Forward Orders '),
(1286, 445, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you do not have enough cash reserves or forward orders to survive in the short term. To survive unforeseen emergencies, every business needs a cash&nbsp;reserve or secure and profitable forward orders that will cover the operating costs of the business.&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Ideally, you should have enough funds coming into your business through&nbsp;sales, or enough cash reserves for at least three months. A three-month buffer will give you some breathing space and time to make alternative plans when things go wrong.&nbsp;If sales are falling, then, you need sufficient cash reserves to allow you to keep trading. Many businesses go through a rough patch and lose money but are able to remain in&nbsp;business by drawing on the profits of previous years that they have retained as savings.&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">If you do not have enough sales coming in to cover costs and you have no reserves, then you need to raise additional cash. You may need to consider using your own personal savings, borrowing more against property, or selling any spare assets to generate&nbsp;some cash. </span></span><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Few Action Points:&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Consider selling some assets. Raise as much money as you can to extend the life of your business such as by selling any assets you do not&nbsp;need or old stock that isn&#39;t</span></span>&nbsp;<span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">moving.&nbsp;</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Try to put as much money back into the business as you can to keep it afloat. Consider selling personal items or seek alternative sources of income.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Make sure your team know it is&nbsp;all hands-on deck. You may be asking them to work longer hours and pull out all the stops until you get through any crisis. So think about how you&rsquo;re going to incentivize, reward, motivate and thank them.&nbsp;</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Control costs as much as possible. Look at your top five expenses. This is where it may be easiest to make the most savings.&nbsp;</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Look at your Profit &amp; Loss statement from last year and work out where you are compared with last year.&nbsp;</span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', '5', 'Cash Reserves and Forward Orders '),
(1287, 446, 'yes', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Make sure you are aware of any impending issues that might throw out your financial planning, such as the need to replace equipment, update technology or increase&nbsp;overheads/resources. Double check that all loans and financial requirements can be met, customers on credit terms are closely monitored, sales forecasts are accurate, and&nbsp;your costs and margins are secure. It is important to know there is nothing coming up that could derail your business financially. The last thing you need is an unexpected&nbsp;expense.&nbsp;Few Action points in this regard are:&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Find out if there are any financial speed bumps in the near future. These could be major, such as needing to repay a large loan you had thought the business could fund.</span></span>&nbsp;<span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Think about external factors such as currency fluctuations, the financial health of your major customers or markets, changes in legislation and changes to your market.&nbsp;</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Check to see if you need to increase overheads or resources that will then throw out your financial planning. Expanding, taking on new staff, opening new outlets or&nbsp;developing new products or services all take time and soak up precious cash. &nbsp;</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Plan for potential problems and manage them, rather than being at the mercy of events. Set out a12 month timeline and plot everything you can think of that might be financially dangerous. Next to each event, outline what you can do to reduce the threat.&nbsp;</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Check if you need to replace old equipment or update obsolete technology to maintain your competitiveness. Can you fund this replacement out of cash flow? Do you really need to update?&nbsp;</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Investigate if you have a client who owes you a disproportionate amount of money. If they pay late, calculate how it will impact on your ability to pay your bills. It may&nbsp;be time to ring or visit them to make sure all is well.</span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', '0', 'Unplanned Future Financial Issues '),
(1288, 446, 'no', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">It is important to know there are no financial issues coming up that could derail your business financially. The last thing you need is an unexpected expense.&nbsp;Keep track of when loans are payable, when equipment will need replacing and other large expenses that could affect your business. Knowing this beforehand allows you to take timely action.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '10', 'Unplanned Future Financial Issues '),
(1289, 447, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Preparing monthly management accounts is a good business practice. It gives the following benefits:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Helps to control costs</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Can send to banks and other financiers</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Can compare to budgets and forecasts</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Helps with cash planning</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Helps in monitoring working capital</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Helps motivate and focus managers or staff that they are shared with.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Avoids big surprises at year end.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Helps to identify seasonal differences.</span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', '16', 'Monthly Management Accounts'),
(1290, 447, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You&nbsp;should prepare monthly management accounts. Preparing monthly management accounts is a good business practice. It gives the following benefits:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Helps to control costs</span></span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Can send to banks and other financiers</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Can compare to budgets and forecasts</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Helps with cash planning</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Helps in monitoring working capital</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Helps motivate and focus managers or staff that they are shared with.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Avoids big surprises at year end.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Helps to identify seasonal differences.</span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', '0', 'Monthly Management Accounts'),
(1291, 448, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Preparation of monthly accounts within a week of month end is a good business practice as it allows you to quickly take corrective action should it become necessary&nbsp;when financial anomalies present themselves. The sooner that accounts become available after month end, the better.</span></span></p>\r\n', '12', ''),
(1292, 448, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">It is really important that you prepare monthly accounts at the end of each month for management review. It is also important to do this quickly so that corrective actions&nbsp;may be taken immediately after financial anomalies present themselves. If you delay getting your management accounts, then you may be late in taking decisions or corrective action that could cost your business.</span></span></p>\r\n', '4', ''),
(1293, 449, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Prompt action by the management in reviewing the accounts is a good sign for any company. This shows that management is alert and is willing to take its decisions based on updated data.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '10', 'Management Review'),
(1294, 449, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Since there is a lag in reviewing the accounts by the management, the sanctity of preparing the same gets diluted. Eventually the quality of reports will also drop as the team would not be motivated to prepare it on a timely basis. &nbsp;Prompt action by the management in reviewing the accounts is required as it will show that management is&nbsp;alert and is willing to take its decisions based on updated data.</span></span></p>\r\n', '4', 'Management Review'),
(1295, 450, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you track financial ratios MOM as well as YOY. &nbsp; This helps the management to compare the results of business operations over different periods of time. Furthermore, such a statement helps in a detailed analysis of the changes in line-wise items of the income statement as well as balance sheet.</span></span></p>\r\n', '14', 'Track Financial Ratios'),
(1296, 450, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you do not track financial ratios MOM as well as YOY. &nbsp;You should start this practice as it will help the management to compare the results of business operations over different periods of time. Furthermore, such a statement helps in a detailed analysis of the changes in line-wise items of the income statement as&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">well as balance sheet.</span></span></p>\r\n', '4', 'Track Financial Ratios'),
(1297, 451, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you create budgets. This is in line with best management practice and it allows you to measure business performance against expectations on an ongoing basis.</span></span></p>\r\n', '14', 'Budgets'),
(1298, 451, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">If you do not prepare financial budgets it is impossible to anticipate revenues and expenditure. It is best management practice to forecast your revenues and expenditure so that you can anticipate peaks and troughs in your cash flow. Also, if you have a budget, you will be able to compare actual results against what you had predicted ahead&nbsp;of time. With practice, your budgeting will tend to get better over time.</span></span></p>\r\n', '6', 'Budgets'),
(1299, 452, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Tracking performance with budgets is one of the purpose of creating budgets. Merits of doing this are:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">The reasons for the overall variances can be easily found out for taking remedial action. </span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Highly useful for fixing responsibility of an individual or department or section for each variance separately.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Useful for Cost Control</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Aids in profit planning</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Creates cost consciousness in the mind of every employee</span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', '10', 'Variance Analysis'),
(1300, 452, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you do not track performance with budgets. Tracking performance with budgets is one of the purpose of creating budgets. Merits of doing this are:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">The reasons for the overall variances can be easily found out for taking remedial action.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Highly useful for fixing responsibility of an individual or department or section for each variance separately.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Useful for Cost Control</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Aids in profit planning</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Creates cost consciousness in the mind of every employee</span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', '2', 'Variance Analysis'),
(1301, 453, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Preparation of cash flow forecast is in line with best business practice. Businesses survive or fall based on their cash flow. Main benefits of cash flow forecast are:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Track your spending</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Identify upcoming cash gaps</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Identify cash surplus</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Track late payers</span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Further, you can take the following actions:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Try increasing your sales across the board by 20% to see how much additional profit you would make. What can you do to achieve this 20% increase?</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Use your cash flow forecast to plan the best times for larger purchases and when to save the cash you need for slower months or seasonality.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">If you are planning to grow your business, use your cash flow forecast to see what would happen if sales doubled. Identify what other stress this might place on&nbsp;resources and how you can overcome these impacts.</span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">In case you are facing any challenges or want to improve the quality of your forecast, you can get in touch with one of our experts.</span></span></p>\r\n', '12', 'Cash Flow Forecast');
INSERT INTO `options` (`id`, `question_id`, `options`, `option_bullet`, `option_answer`, `option_point`, `option_header`) VALUES
(1302, 453, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You should get into a practice of preparing a cash flow forecast on a periodic basis. Preparation of cash flow forecast is in line with best business practice. Businesses survive or fall based on their cash flow. Main benefits of cash flow forecast are:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Track your spending</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Identify upcoming cash gaps</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Identify cash surplus</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Track late payers</span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Further, you can take the following actions:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Try increasing your sales across the board by 20% to see how much additional profit you would make. What can you do to achieve this 20% increase?</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Use your cash flow forecast to plan the best times for larger purchases and when to save the cash you need for slower months or seasonality.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">If you&#39;re planning to grow your business, use your cash flow forecast to see what would happen if sales doubled. Identify what other stresses this might place on resources and how you can&nbsp;overcome these impacts.</span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">In case you are facing any challenges in preparing a cash flow forecast, you can get in touch with one of our experts.</span></span></p>\r\n', '3', 'Cash Flow Forecast'),
(1303, 454, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You are doing a commendable job of not only preparing but reviewing the cash flow projections at regular intervals. This helps you to be in complete control of your cash flows and also improves the quality of your projections over a period of time.</span></span></p>\r\n', '12', ''),
(1304, 454, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Unless and until you review your cash flow projections at regular intervals with your Finance team it will not give you complete control over your cash flows.</span></span></p>\r\n', '3', ''),
(1305, 455, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you are happy with your computer system and it helps you to run your business effectively. This should not make you complacent. In fact you should&nbsp;be aware of the latest technological developments impacting your business and should always be open to adapting if beneficial.</span></span></p>\r\n', '25', 'Effectiveness of Computer System'),
(1306, 455, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that you are not happy with your computer system and it does not help you to run your business effectively. You need to find out the reasons for the same&nbsp;and take corrective action. In fact you should be aware of the latest technological developments impacting your business and should always be open to adapting if beneficial.</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', 'Effectiveness of Computer System'),
(1307, 456, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that your entire staff has access to network drive or the shared drive. This is important as it provides the following benefits:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\"><strong>File sharing</strong> - you can easily share data between different users, or access it remotely if you keep it on other connected devices.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\"><strong>Resource sharing</strong> - using network-connected peripheral devices like printers, scanners and copiers, or sharing software between multiple users, saves money.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\"><strong>Sharing a single internet connection </strong>- it is cost-efficient and can help protect your systems if you properly secure the network.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\"><strong>Increasing storage capacity </strong>- you can access files and multimedia, such as images and music, which you store remotely on other machines or network-attached storage&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">devices.</span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', '25', 'Access to Network Drive'),
(1308, 456, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that your entire staff does not have access to network drive or the shared drive. This is important as it provides the following benefits:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\"><strong>File sharing</strong> - you can easily share data between different users, or access it remotely if you keep it on other connected devices.</span></span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\"><strong>Resource sharing</strong> - using network-connected peripheral devices like printers, scanners and copiers, or sharing software between multiple users, saves money.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\"><strong>Sharing a single internet connection </strong>- it is cost-efficient and can help protect your systems if you properly secure the network.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\"><strong>Increasing storage capacity </strong>- you can access files and multimedia, such as images and music, which you store remotely on other machines or network-attached storage&nbsp;</span></span><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">devices.</span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', '0', 'Access to Network Drive'),
(1309, 457, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">With the constant evolution IT solutions, and particularly the growing popularity of &ldquo;Cloud&rdquo; computing, there can be no excuse for not having a backup solutaion for your computer records both on-site and off-site. You should review the nature of your backup protocols on a regular basis to ensure they meet the evolving needs of the business and offer you robust protection for all of your electronic data. It is no longer enough to have a single backup disk or tape that could be destroyed in a catastrophic event.</span></span></p>\r\n', '25', 'Data Backup'),
(1310, 457, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Imagine if all the data on your computer system was to disappear overnight. You would have no customer records, no financial records, no electronic correspondence&nbsp;files, no electronic employee files. The time and cost involved in rebuilding your company information would be enormous. You can never foresee that devastating flood,&nbsp;fire or storm that could destroy your business records. For this reason, it is sensible to have a robust backup protocol that does a backup of all of your data at the end of each&nbsp;day. This would allow you to reconstruct your business records within 24 hours rather than in weeks or months. Some of the better backup solutions allow you to have one&nbsp;copy of the data in a fireproof safe on your premises and a second copy stored off-site in a secure location or perhaps on a remote server. &nbsp;&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', 'Data Backup'),
(1311, 458, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Since you have a team of people who can handle IT related issues, you are comfortably placed to run systems smoothly.</span></span></p>\r\n', '25', 'IT Team'),
(1312, 458, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Since you do not have a team of people who can handle IT related issues, you either outsource the same or create an in-house team.</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', 'IT Team'),
(1313, 459, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that the management backgrounds are in line with business model. A business model is the foundation for your company and products. It captures the&nbsp;main idea of how your business will generate revenue. It is always good to have a management who have relevant experience and backgrounds which are in line with the&nbsp;business model.</span></span></p>\r\n', '5', 'Backgrounds'),
(1314, 459, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that the management backgrounds are not in line with business model. A business model is the foundation for your company and products. It captures the<br />\r\nmain idea of how your business will generate revenue. It is always good to have a management who have relevant experience and backgrounds which are in line with the<br />\r\nbusiness model. Well, if you are already aware of some deficiencies in your management team then why have you not done something about it? Running a business is all<br />\r\nabout taking prompt corrective action.</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', 'Backgrounds'),
(1315, 460, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Since the management background add value to the customers, are you highlighting this in all your marketing campaigns? If yes, then you are doing great. If no, then start highlighting this fact in all your marketing campaigns henceforth to take maximum benefit of this fact.</span></span></p>\r\n', '10', ''),
(1316, 460, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">At present, you do not have management background to add value for customers. We would recommend you to introspect the benefits of getting someone or a group of people in your management who may bring on board value to existing customer base. This may also lead to your adding a vertical to the existing line of business or at least addition of revenue if marketed well.</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', ''),
(1317, 461, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Since your staff hold you in good faith and trust that you do what you commit is a great sign for any company. Continue doing so and it will reap benefits forever.</span></span></p>\r\n', '15', 'Perception by Staff'),
(1318, 461, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Since your staff feels that you do not stand by your words, there is a trust deficit. Try to build trust amongst your team and it will give rich dividends.</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', 'Perception by Staff'),
(1319, 462, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that the leadership skills of the top management is very inspiring. Continue to be the role model.</span></span></p>\r\n', '15', 'Leadership Style'),
(1320, 462, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You need to mould your behaviour in order to inspire your team.</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', 'Leadership Style'),
(1321, 463, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">The team is not completely aligned to the business goals. They are not comfortable discussing frankly with the management what they feel. Steps should be taken to ensure that there is a culture within the organisation where people have healthy discussions and participate in the formulation of business goals.</span></span></p>\r\n', '15', 'Team Alignment'),
(1322, 463, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">The company culture within the company is good where the staff is completely aligned to business strategies, goals and tactics.</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', 'Team Alignment'),
(1323, 464, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that the Key Managers show respect for each other. This implies that the bonding within the team is good and company should continue to take steps for it remain to healthy. This will help in creating a healthy work culture within the company.</span></span></p>\r\n', '5', ''),
(1324, 464, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that the Key Managers show respect for each other. This implies that the bonding within the team is not good and company should take adequate steps to ensure that it improves. This will help in creating a healthy work culture within the company.</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', ''),
(1325, 465, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">It is great that the management is keeping the staff completely aligned and giving them the power as well as holding them accountable for their actions. This way staff gets a sense of ownership.</span></span></p>\r\n', '10', ''),
(1326, 465, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Management should try to align the staff to the business goals. There is no greater power for the management than to have a team which is completely aligned to its goals. Also, system should be developed where the staff should be held accountable for their actions and necessary power should also be vested in them.</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', ''),
(1327, 466, 'Daily \r\n', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that the senior management team meets daily. It is a good practice that the management is meeting on a daily basis and taking prompt corrective action where necessary.</span></span></p>\r\n', '10', 'Frequency of Meeting'),
(1328, 466, 'Weekly', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that the senior management team meets weekly. It is a good practice that the management is meeting on a weekly basis and taking prompt corrective action where necessary.</span></span></p>\r\n', '10', 'Frequency of Meeting'),
(1329, 466, 'Monthly \r\n', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that the senior management team meets monthly. Management should schedule more meetings frequently to resolve the issues if there is something important to address. Else it is fine if they meet on a monthly basis.</span></span></p>\r\n', '5', 'Frequency of Meeting'),
(1330, 466, 'Quarterly\r\n', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that the senior management team meets quarterly. Management should schedule more meetings frequently to resolve the issues if there is something important to address. Else it is fine if they meet on a quarterly basis.</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', 'Frequency of Meeting'),
(1331, 466, 'Half yearly/Annually\r\n', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that the senior management team meets either half yearly/annually. Management should schedule meetings more frequently to meet. They should meet at least on a quarterly basis and if there is some important agenda to be discussed then they should meet as and when such agenda needs to be discussed.</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', 'Frequency of Meeting'),
(1332, 467, 'Weekly  \r\n', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that the Management meets the staff on a weekly basis to discuss business issues. It is a good practice that the management is meeting the staff timely and taking prompt corrective action where necessary. This way the staff also feels motivated and always on their toes.</span></span></p>\r\n', '10', ''),
(1333, 467, 'Monthly\r\n', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that the Management meets the staff on a monthly basis to discuss business issues. It is a good practice that the management is meeting the staff timely and taking prompt corrective action where necessary. This way the staff also feels motivated and remain always on their toes. However, the management should schedule&nbsp;meetings as and when required to resolve or discuss any important issues as and when they arise.</span></span></p>\r\n', '5', ''),
(1334, 467, 'Quarterly\r\n', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that the Management meets the staff on a quarterly basis to discuss business issues. It is fine that the management is meeting on a quarterly basis. However, the management should schedule meetings as and when required to resolve or discuss any important issues as and when they arise. Meeting frequently will enable&nbsp;management to take prompt corrective action. Also, the staff feels motivated and they feel they are part of the company when they are involved in the problem solving and&nbsp;decision-making activities.</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', ''),
(1335, 467, 'Half yearly/Annually\r\n', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that the Management meets the staff on a half yearly/annual basis to discuss business issues. Management should meet more often to resolve the issues.&nbsp;Meeting frequently will enable management to take prompt corrective action. Also, the staff feels motivated and they feel they are part of the company when they are&nbsp;involved in the problem solving and decision making activities.</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', ''),
(1336, 468, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">It is great to have a team of natural leaders. This will eventually help you to outgrow your competition.</span></span></p>\r\n', '5', 'Leadership Team'),
(1337, 468, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">Adequate steps should be taken to train key executives in their leadership skills. This will help them to delegate effectively and function in a way that they use their resources optimally.</span></span></p>\r\n', '0', 'Leadership Team'),
(1338, 469, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that MIS give you all the management information that you need. Data is the new gold and different types of MIS reports are what help you understand data and use it for your benefit. In order to make informed decisions its important to have access to the data in your company at the right time.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '25', 'MIS'),
(1339, 469, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">You mentioned that MIS does not give you all the management information that you need. Data is the new gold and different types of MIS reports are what help you understand data and use it for your benefit. In order to make informed decisions its important to have access to the data in your company at the right time. You should immediately work on creating an effective MIS system which will fulfil all your needs. In case you find it difficult to prepare it, you can get in touch with one of our experts<br />\r\nwho can help you in this</span></span></p>\r\n', '10', 'MIS'),
(1340, 470, 'yes', 'greenbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">One of the most important purpose of MIS is to track and identify KPIs. Since you are already doing it, it&rsquo;s a job well done.</span></span></p>\r\n', '15', 'KPIs'),
(1341, 470, 'no', 'redbullet.png', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif\">One of the most important purpose of MIS is to track and identify KPIs. Since your MIS is not able to do so, you need to modify your MIS in such a way so that all the KPIs are captured and tracked on a regular basis.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '5', 'KPIs'),
